Polybius, t e emi· nent historian, native of Megalopolis in Arcadia, was born about tac. 204, He was chief of the Achaean league after Philopoemen and one of the 1000 Achaeans sent to Rome to answer the charge of not having assisted the Romans against Perseus. At Rome he remained seventeen years in the house of Aemilius Paulus, of whose son, Scipio Africanus minor, he became the friend, and joined him in his campaign at Carthage and was present at the destruction of that city rac. 146. His history, consisting of forty books, was divided into two parts. The first part comprises a period of fifty-three years, beginning with the second Punic war lac. 218, and ending with the conquest of the Macedonian kingdom rac. 168. The second part comprised the period from the conquest of Perseus to the fall of Corinth tac. 146. The passage here referred to isin a fragment of Book vl 56 fl. Livy xx11 61 says that according to one account they all remained behind in Rome, and only the three returned, whom Hannibal had sent after them, because they did not return as soon as he expected.
